So way back in the 1930s the Roosevelt administration was looking for a way to restrict the ownership of most firearms ostensibly in order to combat their use by organized crime. In the original draft of the National Firearms Act, all handguns were to be subject to its new regulations, which meant that an American who wanted to purchase a handgun would have to pay a $200 tax (at the time, a fee multiple times the cost of the handgun itself) and register it with the US Federal government. To prevent people from purchasing rifles or shotguns and cutting down their stocks and barrels to make them handgun-size and thus circumventing this tax, a provision was inserted into the law that any firearm that was once manufactured with a shoulder stock and a barrel length of >18" would also be subject to regulation if shortened below a certain length. However, the handgun portion of the new regulations was stripped from the law before it was passed in 1934, leaving just the bit which was to penalize people who tried to get around the now non-existent pistol regulations.

>>176432667
Az ainuk főleg/főként Észak-Japánban éltek.
Good effort, just remember that ethnicities (and languages) are not capitalized in Hungarian. Furthermore, you will always have to use the plural form when you refer to an ethnicity as a whole.
Cardinal directions are a bit different in Hungarian. When you put an -i at the end of a cardinal direction it is usually used with seas, mountains, the North Pole, the South Pole etc. There are some exceptions but with countries it's always just "észak, dél, kelet, nyugat."
The rules for the names of geographical units are very nuanced and very hard to keep in mind, especially the hyphens, so don't worry about missing the hyphen here. When you use a cardinal direction to refer to a part of a country you always hyphenate the direction and the name of the country and you capitalize both.

A barátom szeret mangákat olvasni az ainukról,
Infinitive generally follow the object.

Miért nem beszéli már sok ember az ainu nyelvet?
This is the best translation I could come up with, considering I am not sure whether "ainuul" is correct or not.
The sentence begins with an interrogative word so the verb takes priority in the sentence. In any other case "már" could precede the verb.
E.g. "Már elment?" "Délutánra már végeztél?" etc. However, "Mikor megy már el?" "Hova mész már megint?" etc.

posts.name: Anonymous

>>176481473
All of which were gradual processes that began before 987. The collapse of central power had already mostly occurred before Hugh Capet's accession, his election being more of a symptom than a cause. And the emergence of feudalism was complete when territorial grants became hereditary, something that allowed the consolidation of feudal states such as the future Normandy while France was still being ruled by Carolingians and Robertians.
The Holy Roman Empire underwent similar changes, from dynastic changes to a collapse of central power and decentralisation, but no one tries to argue that it was a different entity before and after these processes that span centuries—some even date its birth to Charles the Great's crowning in 800. France being born in 987 is a historiographic construction.

posts.name: Anonymous
posts.com:
>>176481881
>France being born in 987 is a historiographic construction.
Sure, but I don't think it's an unreasonable one. Even in the middle 10th century there was no clear delineation between West and East Francia and the political will to unify both would not end until Otto II's failed attempt of putting the two back together again. 843 just doesn't make sense for the date as there was no separate political entity born from it, it still just formed a part of greater Francia and is ostensibly a foreign Kingdom to Capetian France. All the way until Charles the Fat it was still no different from the 'sub kingdoms' under Charlemagne and even the sort of his father and uncle.

Only after the deposition of Charles the Fat did the collapse of central power into Feudalism accelerate uncontrollably and what we could today see as permanent divisions between the Kingdoms, but that can only be said with foresight. The political community in Germany and in France on Charles' deposition was more or less one in the same, taking over a century and successive wars to break it apart.
